ce:section.ce:para:
As shown in Table 1
                        , the opacity of the films increased significantly with higher concentrations of ZnO or 8 %-ZnO/CQD (p < 0.05), resulting in reduced transparency. This trend is consistent with prior research that reports lower transparency in nanocomposite films as the nanoparticle content increases (Hou et al., 2019; Roy & Rhim, 2021; Roy et al., 2019). The color analysis showed that an increase in the concentration of ZnO or 8 %-ZnO/CQD led to a significant reduction in L∗ values and an elevation in b∗ values (p < 0.05), while a∗ values remained stable (p > 0.05). Despite these changes, visual assessment of the films positioned over text (Fig. 3
                        ) confirmed that the embedded nanoparticles did not compromise readability, indicating that the films retain adequate transparency for consumers to assess food quality visually.

Table 2
 presents the tensile strength (TS), elongation at break (EAB), and oxygen permeability of the films. Optimal packaging materials must possess robust mechanical properties and effective barrier functions to prevent contamination, tearing, and degradation during storage. The TS and EAB parameters evaluate the mechanical integrity of the films, which is contingent upon interactions within the biopolymer matrix and incorporated nanoparticles (Candra et al., 2023). The 8ZCA8 film exhibited the highest TS; however, there were no significant differences among the films (p > 0.05). Conversely, EAB was significantly enhanced in ZA8 and 8ZCA8 compared to the Agar film (p < 0.05), with 8ZCA8 demonstrating the greatest flexibility. The films exhibited thicknesses ranging from approximately 0.030 to 0.039 mm, with no significant variance noted (p > 0.05, Table 3
). Maintaining low oxygen permeability is essential for extending the shelf life of food products, while moderate permeability supports respiration, microbial activity, and color retention in fresh produce, fermented food, and meat (Jafarzadeh & Jafari, 2021). OTR was significantly lower in films containing ZnO or 8 %-ZnO/CQD compared to the Agar film (p < 0.05, Table 3), with 8ZCA8 exhibiting the lowest OTR. Several studies have similarly reported that the inclusion of CQD reduced oxygen permeability in films (Ezati et al., 2022; Fan et al., 2020; Lin et al., 2022; Wen et al., 2023). Water contact angle (WCA) measurements were conducted to assess film hydrophobicity (Fig. 5
). A higher WCA indicates enhanced hydrophobicity, improving moisture resistance in food packaging. Moreover, WCA influences wettability, which affects bacterial attachment, proliferation, and viability, thereby impacting the functionality of the film (Liu et al., 2021). As depicted, the WCA values of ZA8 and 8ZCA8 films were higher than those of the Agar film, with substantial differences observed among the three films (p < 0.05). A surface is deemed hydrophilic if the WCA is below 65° (Pulla-Huillca et al., 2021), indicating that only the Agar film exhibited hydrophilic properties, whereas ZA8 and 8ZCA8 films were hydrophobic.
